title: tetsujin_28
body:
[b]Tetsujin 28-gou[/b] (literally translated as "Iron Man No. 28"), is the titular [[super robot]] [[mecha]] from [[Tetsujin 28-gou]], which is widely considered to be one of the first super robot character ever.

An extremely clunky yet near-indestructible robot, Tetsujin has a [[knight]] helmet-like head with iconic spiky nose, a bright yellow eyes which acts as an ultra-bright spotlight, and a massive [[jetpack]] at the back. As one of the earliest giant robot character, it lacks any weapon or special power, thus relies only on its extremely strong body and brute strength to defeat its adversaries. It is remote-controlled by [[Kaneda Shoutarou (Tetsujin 28-gou)|]].

h4. See also

title: scarlet_ibis_(kemono_friends)
body:
A type of avian Friend that has appeared in all Kemono Friends media to date.

Scarlet Ibis dresses in a long, red coat with a puffy, feather-like collar and matching sleeves. She wears a pink skirt with peach-coloured stockings that go up to her thighs and also dons a pair of ruby-red Mary Janes. Scarlet Ibis' hair is predictably scarlet in colour, with black tips on either end of the long hair locks hanging from her bangs. This colouration closely resembles the beak of the actual bird. Her hair is tied in the back in two thin pigtails, and a pair of tiny, four-tone wings protrude from her head. She has a feathery tail with black tips. Her eyes are a garnet red.

While still four-toned, Scarlet Ibis' wing tips were originally white in colouration rather than black. In addition, she wore black shoes and apparently used different hair ties to hold her pigtails together. Rather than thigh-high stockings, she wore full leggings. Notably, her eyes are grey in colour.

title: help:user_records
body:
The user feedback system is a way of recognizing users for positive or negative behavior. Positive feedback can be given to a user to recognize their contributions to Danbooru, or to recommend them for promotion. Neutral or negative feedback can be given to bring attention to disruptive or [[help:upload_rules|rule-breaking]] behavior.

Feedbacks can be seen on a user's profile, or on the "User Feedbacks page":[/user_feedbacks].

Feedback can only be given by Gold users or above. To give a user a feedback, hover your mouse over their name, click the "..." menu, and click Give Feedback. Alternatively, go to the "User Feedbacks page":[/user_feedbacks] and click "New":[/user_feedbacks/new] at the top.

There are three types of feedback: positive, neutral, and negative. Positive feedbacks are given for good behavior, and negative feedbacks are for bad behavior. Neutral feedbacks are given as warnings, and automatically by the site for things like promotions or demotions.  

Negative feedback should be given sparingly. Before giving a user a negative feedback, you should communicate with them privately to tell them what they're doing wrong and how to improve. Negative feedback should only be given for flagrant rule violations, or for continued bad behavior after having been warned. A neutral feedback should normally be given first, unless the user is deliberately breaking the rules, such as engaging in intentional vandalism or sockpuppeting.

If you have received a negative feedback, and you think it's unfair, or the problem has been resolved, you can appeal to have it removed by petitioning the mods or admins on the forum.

title: konnyaku_(food)
body:
[b]Konnyaku[/b], also called konjac, konjak, or konjaku, is a food product made from the corms of the [[konjac (plant)|]] plant ([i]Amorphophallus konjac[/i]), grown in Japan and elsewhere in east/southeast Asia.

The corms are made into a jelly-like, rectangular brick of food-stuff. It is basically flavorless, and is usually an ingredient in more complex foods rather than eaten straight. It is frequently used as a vegan substitute for [[gelatin]]. Unlike gelatin, however, konnyaku can be a choking hazard if not properly chewed.

Konnyaku is used in making [[oden]], [[lychee]] cups and konjac candy, a thick Jello-like snack made with fruit paste to flavor the konnyaku. Konnyaku can also be pressed through a mesh to create gelatinous noodles called [i]shirataki[/i], often used in Japanese soups like [i][[sukiyaki]][/i] or [i][[gyuudon]][/i].  

Konnyaku is low in calories and high in fiber, so it is frequently used as diet food.

The NLAW, also known as the MBT LAW or RB 57, is a fire-and-forget, lightweight shoulder-fired, and disposable line of sight (LOS) missile system, designed for infantry use. The system was developed in Sweden by prime contractor Saab Bofors Dynamics, on behalf of the British and Swedish defence authorities who procured the system in a joint venture. The missile uses a soft-launch system and is guided by predicted line of sight (PLOS). It can carry out an overfly top attack (OTA) on an armoured vehicle, or a direct attack (DA) on structures and non-armoured vehicles.

Any image depicting the [[moon]] with a distinct red tint or glow.  Also called a "blood moon."  This is often considered an evil omen.

In real life, the moon turns red during a total [[lunar eclipse]] because sunlight is completely blocked by [[Earth (planet)|]] and the only light reflected from its surface has been refracted from Earth's atmosphere, which is red in color for the same reason that a sunrise or sunset turns the sky red.

title: clara_oswald
body: Clara Oswald is a fictional character in the British science fiction television series [[Doctor Who]]. She was created by series producer Steven Moffat and portrayed by Jenna Coleman. Clara was introduced in the seventh series as a new travelling companion of the series protagonist, the Doctor, in his eleventh and twelfth incarnations. Coleman received top billing alongside Matt Smith and Peter Capaldi for the duration of her time as a regular cast member. A featured actress in the series seven premiere, she became a regular for the second part of said series (2012), the 50th anniversary specials (2013), all of series eight (2014) and series nine (2015). Coleman also reappeared briefly in the 2017 Christmas special. This makes her one of the longest-serving companions in the show's history.

title: vanishing_point
body:
Use this tag when the [[perspective]] of a picture appears to draw the viewer's eye towards a central point.  An example might be a city street as seen from the center of the road.

Convergence of the background of an image towards a single point is the key.  Do not confuse this for any use of [[perspective]] -- e.g., most [[checkered floor|checkered floors]]. For example, post #140887 just has [[perspective]], but post #1341879 has a [[vanishing point]].

It is possible for an image to contain multiple vanishing points, especially if you're viewing a scene from an angle. See, e.g. post #1312088.

This is an artistic technique, so don't bother with images with a [[photo background]] unless it's a major focus of the image. One can assume nature gets it right.

title: bionicle
body:
A [[the lego group|LEGO]] [[toy]]line of constraction figures that ran from 2000 to 2010. The series features many [[science fiction]] elements as well as influence from Maori aesthetics and language, and is notable for having incredibly expansive lore and an ongoing story throughout the line's lifetime. The lore was spread across a variety of mediums, including books, comics, video games, flash games, podcasts, and 4 feature-length films.

LEGO rebooted the line in 2015, with a new continuity and completely different art style. The reboot featured several books, graphic novels, animated web shorts, and an animated series on [[Netflix]], before being discontinued in 2016.

Despite the line being in a dormant state and having no new official content releases or reprints of previous sets, the series has retained a large fanbase that consistently creates new content.

h4. See also
* [[Kanohi (Bionicle)|]]
* [[Matoran Language]]
* [[Hero Factory]] - spiritual successor line that briefly replaced Bionicle after its discontinuation.

body:
Victoria Harbour is a natural landform harbour in Hong Kong separating Hong Kong Island in the south from the Kowloon Peninsula to the north. The harbour's deep, sheltered waters and strategic location on South China Sea were instrumental in Hong Kong's establishment as a British colony in 1841 and its subsequent development as a trading centre.

title: warthog
body:
A type of wild [[boar]] that lives in open and semi-open habitats, even in quite arid regions, in sub-Saharan [[Africa]]. The two species of warthogs were formerly considered conspecific under the scientific name [i]Phacochoerus aethiopicus[/i], but today this is limited to the [[desert]] warthog.

* [b]Common warthog[/b] ([i]Phacochoerus africanus[/i]). The best-known, most widespread species. Widespread in the [[savannah]] of Sub-Saharan Africa from Senegal to Ethiopia down to South Africa, absent from heavily forested or desert areas.
* [b]Desert warthog[/b] ([i]Phacochoerus aethiopicus[/i]). Its distribution ranges from Northern Kenya and Somalia, and possibly Djibouti, Eritrea, and Ethiopia.

Warthogs are seen covered in earthy brown bristly hairs, their bodies and heads appear largely naked from a distance, with only the crest along the back, and the tufts on their cheeks and tails being obviously haired. The term [i]warthog[/i] refers to their facial wattles, which are particularly distinct in males. They also have very distinct [[tusks]], which reach a length of 25 to 64 centimetres in the males, but are always smaller in the females. Warthogs are omnivorous, with most of their diet consist of plant materials and occasionally eat small [[animal]]s.

* [[Pumbaa]], the main character of [[The Lion King]] is a warthog.
* [b]Hoglin[/b], a large hostile mob in [[Minecraft]] that spawns in the Nether dimension strongly resembles the warthog.

title: deadmau5
body:
Joel Thomas Zimmerman (born January 5, 1981),[2] known professionally as Deadmau5 (stylized as deadmau5; pronounced "dead-mouse"), is a Canadian electronic music producer and DJ. He mainly produces progressive house music, though he also produces and DJs other genres of electronic music, including techno under the alias Testpilot. Zimmerman has received six Grammy Award nominations for his work.

He has worked with other DJs and producers, such as Kaskade, Wolfgang Gartner, Rob Swire, and Chris Lake. He has also collaborated with Steve Duda under the group name BSOD (Better Sounding On Drugs), and was part of the group named WTF? with Duda, Tommy Lee and DJ Aero. In 2007, he founded his own record label, Mau5trap. Deadmau5 is currently one of the highest paid electronic music producers in the world,[3] and is a masked music artist similar to Marshmello and Daft Punk.[4] His works have been included in compilation albums such as Tiësto's In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza, and presented on Armin van Buuren's A State of Trance radio show.

title: help:saved_searches
body:
Saved searches allow you to save frequently used tag searches. They also provide a convenient way to check for new posts under a given search. Using saved searches, you can find updates by your favorite artists, characters, pools, or [[help:cheatsheet|anything else you can search for]].

h4. Adding a search

* Perform a search from the "posts":/posts page.
* Click the "Save search" button under the Options header in the menu to the left of the search results.
* Optionally name your search in the Labels section of the dialogue box that appears.
* Click "Submit".

h4. Viewing searches

To check for new posts among your saved searches, visit your user profile by following the My Account link in the navbar.

h4. Editing searches

To manage your existing saved searches, visit your "saved searches":/saved_searches page.

h4. Features

The following represents the current functionality of saved searches:

* Each saved search will return the most recent 1,000 posts matching that tag query.
* A saved search can have several labels. Labels allow you to organize your saved searches into different groups.
* If you have a gold account, you can view all posts for a single category, or across all saved searches.
* Saved searches are updated once an hour.
* Platinum users can have at most 1,000 saved searches, Builder users can have unlimited saved searches, and everyone else can have at most 250 saved searches.

h4. See also

* [[help:tag subscriptions]] - tag subscriptions have been replaced by saved searches.

title: voodoo_doll
body:
On [[danbooru_(site)|danbooru]], two types of curse [[doll]]s are referred to as it. - [[Voodoo doll]]s and [i][[Straw doll]][/i]s.

Voodoo dolls are [[doll]]s that are used by Houngans (Voodoo [[priest]]s) in curse rituals. It is well known that by stabbing a doll with a [[pin]], the person who is the target of the curse is hurt in the same place as the doll. In reality, this kind of curse didn't exist in the original Voodoo. It is thought that the practice was imagined by the writer of some movie or novel. These dolls can be obtained easily as a souvenir in Haiti.

title: mirai_shounen_conan
body:
[i][b]Future Boy Conan[/b][/i] (未来少年コナン [i]Mirai Shōnen Konan[/i]) is a 70s post-apocalyptic [[science fiction]] anime series which premiered across Japan on the NHK network between April 4 and October 31, 1978 on the Tuesday 19:30-20:00 timeslot. The official English title used by Nippon Animation is [i][b]Conan, The Boy in Future[/b][/i].

The anime is set in a post-apocalyptic Earth covered almost entirely by water, a result of the terrible and advanced electromagnetic weaponry used during World War III. 

Spanning a total of 26 episodes, the series was produced by Nippon Animation and featured [[miyazaki_hayao_(person)|Miyazaki Hayao]] (director, character designs, storyboards), Takahata Isao (storyboards) and [[Tomino Yoshiyuki]] (storyboards). It is an adaptation of "Alexander Key":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Key 's 1970 Sci-Fi novel [i]"The Incredible Tide":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Incredible_Tide [/i].

A [[video game]] version of the series by Telenet Japan was released in 1992 on NEC's [[PC Engine]] console. The game was released on the Super CD-Rom format and was only available in Japan. A [[PlayStation 2]] action and adventure game adaptation was also released in 2005 only in Japan.

Kracko is also one of many [[Demon Beast|Demon Beasts]] in the anime. He still shoots lightning bolts, but now he also hides within his own flying fortress in the form of a massive group of black clouds. He appears in Episode 4 of the anime.

title: eye_chart
body:
An eye chart is a standardized test used to measure a person's visual acuity. Consists of a table of characters of decreasing size, usually from the top down. The test taker then identifies the characters until they become too small for them to do so.

Common in Japan is the [[Landolt C]] test, where the chart contains circles with small gaps and the subject has to determine on which side the gap lies. Eye charts that use Latin letters, such as the "Snellen chart":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snellen_chart or "LogMAR chart":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LogMAR_chart", are common in countries that use the Latin alphabet.

Visual acuity is measured by two numbers, where the first number is the distance the subject needs to read something and the second number is the distance a normal person needs. In America, it is standard for the first number to be 20 (feet), with 20/20 being normal vision. In Japan and countries that use the metric system, the standard is 6 (meters), with normal vision being 6/6.

title: granzon
body:
The Granzon is one of the first machines developed by the Divine Crusaders. The design is planned out by [[Shu Shirakawa]], a member of the faction and a good friend of their leader, [[Bian Zoldark]]. The Granzon is so costly to develop and construct that it consumed two-thirds of the Divine Crusader's budget. It's also known that Shu used alchemy from La Gias to enhance the power of the Granzon.

The Granzon uses an antimatter annihilation engine, a perfectly efficient energy source. The annihilation engine is able to meet the immense energy requirements of the Granzon's weapon systems, which all involve gravity and time-space manipulation. An advanced artificial intelligence program also allows the Granzon to engage up to 65,536 enemies at once. So far, the only units said to be able to hold the Granzon one-on-one are the [[Astranagant]], Dis Astranagant, [[Shurouga]], [[Cybuster]] (in its full possession mode), and Zelvoid (in its full possession mode). 

Using the Kabbalah System Shu can turn the Granzon into the [[Neo Granzon]], one of the strongest mechs in the [[Super Robot Wars]] multiverse.

The Power Lifter (運搬着 パワーリフター Unpan-gi, lit. "Transport Clothes") is a heavy [[machinery]] used in the transportation of cargo and other large objects. Not like the military [[Powered Suit (toaru)|]]s, it is a humanoid-shaped [[exoskeleton]] that the operator wears on their backs.

title: yamada_asaemon_jikka
body:
Yamada Asaemon Jikka is the former 3rd ranked Asaemon in the Yamada clan.

After the shogun called for criminals to acquire the Elixir of Life from the dangerous island known as Kotaku, in exchange for a pardon for their past crimes, Jikka joined in the expedition team as one of the Yamada Asaemon monitors and was assigned to keep watch over the criminal, [[Horubo (Jigokuraku)|]]. [spoiler] However, his mission was cut short after the death of his criminal at sea and was required to return back to the mainland. [/spoiler]

title: gabimaru
body:
The protagonist of the manga series [[Jigokuraku]].

Gabimaru, born as Tsuki, is an elite shinobi assassin formerly from Iwagakure and the last holder of the infamous alias, Gabimaru the Hollow. He is also the husband of [[Yui (Jigokuraku)|]], the eighth daughter to the Iwagakure chief.

Upon taking the mission to acquire the Elixir of Life from the dangerous island known as Kotaku, [[Yamada Asaemon Sagiri]] was chosen as his assigned monitor.
